      {
        "type": "regex",
        "pattern": "\\b[a-f0-9]{32}\\b",
        "message": "Slack OAuth Client Secret detected in source code. This 32-character hexadecimal string is a highly sensitive credential that provides full authentication capability for your Slack OAuth application. Exposing the Client Secret enables attackers to: complete OAuth flows and obtain access tokens, impersonate your application to any Slack workspace, access all data and perform all actions permitted by your app's OAuth scopes, install or reinstall your app in workspaces without authorization, bypass security controls and user consent flows, and potentially access private channels, user data, and workspace information. This is a critical security vulnerability. Take immediate action: revoke the compromised Client Secret in the Slack App Management console (https://api.slack.com/apps), generate a new Client Secret immediately, update all production systems and services with the new secret, rotate any potentially compromised access tokens obtained with this secret, store Client Secret in secure secret management systems (AWS Secrets Manager, HashiCorp Vault, Azure Key Vault), never commit secrets to version control or expose them in logs, use environment variables with restricted access, implement secret scanning and monitoring in CI/CD pipelines, enable audit logging for your Slack app, use different credentials for each environment (dev/staging/prod), and review Slack workspace access logs for unauthorized activity.",
